by the New York Times, New Orleans Times-Picayune, Time, Newsweek, NBC, and CNN, as well as the works of artists, writers, musicians, filmmakers, and graphic designers, Ron Eyerman analyzes how these narratives publicly articulated collective pain and loss. He demonstrates that, by exposing a foundational racial cleavage in American society, these expressions of cultural trauma turned individual experiences of suffering during Katrina into a national debate about the failure of the white majority in the United States to care about the black minority.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aDisaster victims -- United States -- Social conditions. 0aDisaster victimszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005 -- Press coverage. 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005 -- Social aspects. 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005xPress coverage. 0aHurricane Katrina, 2005xSocial aspects. 0aPsychic trauma -- Social aspects -- Louisiana -- New Orleans. 0aPsychic traumaxSocial aspectszLouisianazNew Orleans. 0aRefugees -- Louisiana -- New Orleans -- Social conditions. 0aRefugeeszLouisianazNew OrleansxSocial conditions. 0aSocial problems -- Psychological aspects. 0aSocial problemsxPsychological aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/30368940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477307465423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477307465/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK